Question: What is the difference between the "==" and "equals()" in Java?
Answer:<<<api>>>: == and equals()
<<<code>>>: String str1 = new String("Hello");
String str2 = new String("Hello");
System.out.println(str1 == str2); // prints false
System.out.println(str1.equals(str2)); // prints true
<<<explanation>>>: The "==" operator in Java compares the memory locations of two objects. It checks whether the two references point to the same object or not. On the other hand, the "equals()" method in Java compares the actual content of the objects. It checks whether the two strings are identical or not.
